    <string name="first_aid_guide_title">Basic Skills Guide</string>
    <string name="first_aid_displacement_title">Displacement Skills</string>
    <string name="first_aid_displacement_summary">Move patients to a safe place away from immediate danger. Avoid movement if a severe spinal injury is suspected unless absolutely necessary.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_displacement_detail">If there are dangers around such as fire or electrical hazards, move the patient to a safe place only if it is safe for the first aid provider to do so.\n\nIf a severe spinal injury is suspected, do not move the patient unless it is absolutely necessary. When movement is unavoidable, do it as little and as carefully as possible.\n\nUsually, the patient should end up lying face-up on a firm surface so chest compressions can be performed if needed.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_checking_title">Checking Skills</string>
    <string name="first_aid_checking_summary">Assess scene safety, responsiveness, bleeding, pulse, and breathing without losing critical time.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_checking_detail">Evaluate the victim’s condition by first addressing immediate threats to life.\n\nCheck responsiveness by tapping the shoulder and speaking loudly.\n\nControl severe bleeding with direct pressure.\n\nIf the patient does not respond, check the carotid or radial pulse.\n\nCheck breathing by looking at the chest and listening for airflow.\n\nDo not spend more than 10 seconds checking breathing and pulse before taking action.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_cpr_title">Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation</string>
    <string name="first_aid_cpr_summary">A life-saving technique that combines chest compressions and rescue breaths when needed.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_cpr_detail">1. Place the heel of one hand on the center of the chest.\n\n2. Place the other hand on top and interlace your fingers.\n\n3. Push hard and fast at least 2 inches deep, about 100 to 120 compressions per minute.\n\n4. Let the chest fully rise between compressions.\n\n5. If you are trained, give 2 rescue breaths after every 30 compressions.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_abc_title">ABC Skills</string>
    <string name="first_aid_abc_summary">Airway, Breathing, and Circulation: check the airway, breathing, and major bleeding in that order.</string>
    <string name="first_aid_abc_detail">A - Airway: Gently tilt the head back and lift the chin to open the airway.\n\nB - Breathing: Look, listen, and feel for normal breathing for no more than 10 seconds.\n\nC - Circulation: Check for severe bleeding. If the person is not breathing normally, begin CPR immediately.\n\nThe patient must have an open airway so air can travel into the lungs. Conscious people do this automatically, but unconscious people may not.\n\nUse the recovery position when appropriate, watch for choking, and move to CPR if breathing is absent or abnormal.</string>
